              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">How to Cheat at Star Wars</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2578"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2578"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=7017">Greg "Gergall" Zinn</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 7017 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">This article takes an in-depth look at the three major ways the players at your neighborhood tournament area cheat at Star Wars: destiny manipulation, rules issues, and "card shark" tactics.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">	There is nothing quite so fulfilling in the Star Wars CCG universe than pulling out a big win against a highly worthy opponent, especially in a tournament setting where prizes are often at stake.  But some players are driven too strongly by the prize incentive; they will do anything for that foil Mara Jade or sealed box of Tatooine.  They wouldn&#146;t agree that the sense of victory and triumph after a hard-fought game is more valuable than a temporary tangible reward.  Some people, unfortunately, will cheat to win.<br>
	First of all, it is my opinion that anyone who cheats has ruined the whole point of the game.  The competition is all about building the best deck of 60 cards that you can, and showing that you can use those cards to win.  Why do the cheaters bother doing this?  Why not simply bring a concealed weapon to the tournament and demand first prize?<br>
	Before I go into the nitty-gritty of cheating, I&#146;d like to state that the occasional loss of memory(both players forgot to draw podrace destiny or lose a force to Visage of the Emperor) isn&#146;t anyones fault.  We are, after all, humans who do make mistakes, and there will not likely be a local sanctioned tournament where every little detail is carried out perfectly.  But at the same time, if a player remembers a rule in effect and consciously chooses or tries to ignore it, well, thats still cheating.  You ARE responsible not only for your own actions and cards on the table but also your opponents.<br>
	I was exposed to the first form of cheating, destiny manipulation, years ago, sometime between the release of Dagobah and Cloud City.  Watching my friends play, I witnessed in horror how one of my friends would casually create a small distraction(&quot;Is that a spider?!&quot;) then place a card from his hand onto his reserve deck.  A moment later he initiates a battle, and surprise, surprise: his battle destiny is a 6.  This particular destiny manipulation is also part of another form of cheating that I call card shark tactics, but more on that later.  There are other forms of illegal destiny tracking.  One popular trick is to place high destiny cards in the used pile upside down(works best with clear deck protectors or no protectors at all).  By upside down, I mean that the symbol(Rebel or Imperial) was facing in a different direction than all of the other cards in the same pile.  Even after a shuffling of the reserve deck, all of the high destinies are still obvious by their reversed logos.  Wow, it takes a real genius to figure that insidious plot out.  Those cheaters can be really proud of themselves.<br>
	The next type of cheater, the rules manipulator, is the kind that most commonly shows up at tournaments.  This kind of guy first tells me that I can&#146;t persona replace his dark Lando because he&#146;s got Lobot at an adjacent site.  After I signal over to the tournament director, my opponent quickly gives in but tells me to pay 6 force for my Lando.  Again, I signal over to the TD and my opponent admits persona replacement is free.  Keep in mind that my opponent is no newbie; his rating is over 1800, through the roof as far as local competition is concerned.  Other high ranked players tried such rule-bending as to treat Dr. Evazen and Ponda Boba(the combo card) as two separate aliens(and thus increase their deploy cost tremendously with The Camp) and trying to treat Zuckess in Mist Hunter as an alien.  Sure, a new player could make these mistakes, but these were experienced players.  Even though I am brand new to the tournament scene, I recognized all of these rules violations.<br>
	The final type of cheater is definitely the most dangerous.  The card shark is very real and very powerful, but no one really knows who he is or exactly how much he is cheating.  He activates too much force, or uses too few.  The only problem is that we have no idea when we&#146;re dealing with a card shark, unless we can catch him in the act.  It just is not viable to count the opponents activation and force use each turn, and anyone who has played in a tournament realizes there is just not enough time for this.  Ever been in the situation where you just needed one more unit of force to cause mass destruction for your opponent?  The card shark never has this problem.  It is unfair, but there is not much we can do.<br>
	I hate the cheating that goes on in local tournaments, but unfortunately most players, honest or not, will never get to experience the pureness of a fairly officiated world championship game.  Despite the cheaters, I will continue to play in local tournaments with my friends and implore my fellow players to do the same.  Do not fall to the dark side.  Play fair, please. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=2578"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=2578"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=2578" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
